observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation and the LCE agreed that the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board, through the SWM Focal Person, (a) establish MRF in the 11 barangays to facilitate the segregation of solid waste at the barangay level; 


(b) coordinate and require all barangays located in the coastal areas to have proper solid waste management disposal and closely monitor their implementation; and 

(c) instruct the barangay officials to inform their barangay collectors/segregators/ sorters to properly sort the wastes they had collected before transferring them to the Central MRF.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
require the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a physical count of property, plant and equipment to determine the existence and condition thereof; (ii) submit the RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records;
require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to (i) maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively; and (ii) reconcile their respective PPE records;
direct all concerned Municipal officials to exert effort in the reproduction of titles on all lots owned by the Municipality and recognize them in the books using the appraised values; and
follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the LCE require the: 

(a) Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a physical count on the property, plant and equipment to determine the existence and condition of the PPEs;




(ii) submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) duly reconciled with the accounting and property records;



(b) Municipal Accountant and the GSO to (i) maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered; and (ii) reconcile the respective records of the Accounting Office and Property Officer on PPE;



(c) concerned Municipal officials to exert effort in the reproduction of titles on all lots owned by the Municipality and recognize them in the book’s lands owned by the Municipality using appraised values; and



Moreover, we also recommended that the LCE require officials to follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the (a) Local Chief Executive and heads of concerned implementing offices agreed to (i) implement without further delay the remaining projects not completed/implemented in CY 2020;

 and (ii) continue to monitor and supervise the effective and efficient implementation of projects funded from various source agencies within the timelines of the MOA, as far as feasible; and 

(b) Municipal Accountant and the Treasurer continue to be prompt in the return of excess funds to the source agencies upon completion or termination of the project.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the (a) MDRRMC to prepare and submit the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) indicating the (i) detailed PPAs and the corresponding appropriation classified as either Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) or Capital Outlay (CO); (ii) under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years for ease of monitoring of project implementation; 

(b) MDRRMC ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized for the implementation of projects and activities for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery; and 

(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) and maintain corresponding Subsidiary Ledger for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment; and (ii) ensure that the amount and details of the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF is discussed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

